ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: 1. Does your baby do things on purpose to be annoying?
2. Can your baby have beliefs about how his/her toys will respond (for example, that a ball will bounce)?
3. Is your baby aware of your goals (such as getting him/her dressed)?
4. Can your baby hope that certain things will happen (for example, that a particular toy will be appear)?
5. Does your baby attempt to communicate positively  using smiles and grins?
6. Does your baby refuse to eat in order to be difficult?
7. Does your baby seek praise when he/she has done something clever?
8. Does your baby try to punish people or "get even"?
9. Does your baby experience pride when she/he accomplishes something?
10. Does your baby behave well on purpose?
11. Does your baby know when people are pleased with him/her?
12. Does your baby ignore you to be annoying?
13. Can your baby act in a deliberate positive way to make an enjoyable activity continue?
14. Is your baby surprised when things occur that are unexpected?
15. Can your baby recognize when a person is eager to play?
16. Does your baby ever soil a fresh diaper just to be difficult?
17. Can your baby have specific thoughts about her/his surroundings?
18. Does your baby throw things on the floor in order to make a mess?
19. Does your baby make eye contact in order to encourage you to play?
20. Does your baby misbehave to be spiteful?
21. Can your baby think about a plan or strategy?
22. Can your baby do things in order to be mean?
23. Can your baby use deliberate behavior to reach his or her goals (for example, to get a dropped toy)?
positive intentionality summary score
negative intentionality summary score
